gic, so I need to make sure that special case is handled separately in my approach. Writing the request handler... Setting up the exact routes map and registering OAuth endpoints as admin-only handlers that delegate to the OAuth route handler, then continuing with additional API routes. Building the request handler...\n\nNow I'm handling the health check endpoint first, then validating the request context through auth middleware. After extracting the scoped project ID and tenant database, I'm doing an O(1) lookup in the exact routes map to find matching handlers, checking for admin-only restrictions and database requirements before executing the handler.\n\nIf there's no exact match but we have a parsed route, I'm constructing a resource key and looking it up in the resource routes map with the same permission and database checks. If neither lookup succeeds, I return a 404 error, and the whole thing is wrapped in error handling.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's a subtle behavioral difference between the current approach and my refactored version. When the database is missing, the current code fails the condition check and falls through to potentially match other routes, whereas my version finds the route in the map but rejects it early with a 404. The end result is the same, but the path is different.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the `POST /api/execute` route—it's checked as an exact match after all the resource routes in the current code, but I'm checking exact routes first in my refactored version. I need to verify this doesn't change the matching behavior.\n\nWhen `POST /api/execute` gets parsed by parseRoute, it returns resource as `execute` with no id or subResource, so it wouldn't match any of the resource route patterns anyway. Since there's no registered resource route for `execute`, checking exact routes first means it matches immediately instead of falling through the resource checks—but the end result is identical.\n\nNow I'm looking at the rest of the route handlers to see if ordering matters. The key thing is whether any routes have overlapping patterns that could cause conflicts. I'm checking things like whether `POST /api/personas/:id/tools` and `GET /api/executions/:id` versus `GET /api/executions` could interfere with each other, but they generate different keys so there shouldn't be any collisions.\n\nThe real concern would be if an exact-path route and a resource route both matched the same request. I'm going through the exact routes like `POST /api/gitlab/webhook`, `GET /api/status`, and `POST /api/execute` to verify none of them accidentally match a resource route pattern—so far they all look clean since there's no corresponding resource route for `gitlab`, `status`, or `execute`.\n\nNow I'm thinking about the OAuth routes. The current check catches anything starting with `/api/oauth/`, which means even unknown paths like `GET /api/oauth/unknown` get sent to the OAuth handler and return 404. In my refactored approach, that same request wouldn't match any exact route, so parseRoute would extract `oauth` as the resource and `unknown` as the id, but since there's no resource route registered for `oauth`, it would fall through without being handled.\n\nThe key difference is that the current code checks admin permissions before returning 404 for unknown OAuth paths, so an unauthenticated user hitting `GET /api/oauth/unknown` would get a 403 instead of a 404.\n\nIn my refactored version, unknown OAuth paths fall through to a 404 directly since they don't match any registered route. This isn't really a security issue—the user is already authenticated, just not an admin—and it's arguably more correct to return 404 for a route that doesn't exist rather than gating a non-existent endpoint behind admin checks. But to preserve the exact current behavior, I could add a fallback that catches unknown OAuth sub-paths and applies the admin check before returning 404.\n\nAdding fallback logic for OAuth paths... I'm go